          <span class="result-value" id="resultDays">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Who Is Older?</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultOlder">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Person 1 Current Age</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultAge1">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Person 2 Current Age</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultAge2">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card success">
          <span class="result-label">Half-Your-Age-Plus-7 Rule</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="resultRule">--</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="calc-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>How to Calculate Age Difference</h2>
    <p>Calculating the age difference between two people is more nuanced than simply subtracting years. While a rough estimate might tell you the gap is about 5 years, the precise difference includes years, months, and days, accounting for the varying lengths of months and the occurrence of leap years. This precision matters in many contexts, from legal age requirements and insurance calculations to relationship milestones and family planning.</p>
    <p>The most straightforward way to calculate an age difference is to subtract the earlier date from the later date. Start with the days: if the day of the later date is smaller than the day of the earlier date, borrow one month (adding the appropriate number of days for the previous month). Then compare the months: if the month of the later date is smaller than the month of the earlier date (after any borrowing), borrow one year by adding 12 to the months. Finally, subtract the years.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Age Difference = Later Birthday - Earlier Birthday (in years, months, days)</code>
    </div>
    <p>For example, if Person A was born on May 15, 1990 and Person B was born on September 20, 1995, the difference is calculated as follows. September 20 minus May 15: the days are 20 minus 15 equals 5 days. The months are 9 minus 5 equals 4 months. The years are 1995 minus 1990 equals 5 years. So the age difference is 5 years, 4 months, and 5 days.</p>
    <p>The total number of days between two dates requires accounting for leap years and varying month lengths. A year has either 365 or 366 days, and months range from 28 to 31 days. The most reliable approach is to convert both dates to a day count from a common reference point and subtract. This is exactly what the calculator above does using JavaScript's Date object, which handles all these complexities automatically.</p>

    <h2>Understanding Current Age Calculation</h2>
    <p>Your current age in years is not simply the current year minus your birth year. You also need to account for whether your birthday has passed this year. If today is March 10 and your birthday is September 20, you have not yet turned a year older in the current calendar year. The calculator computes the exact current age by comparing the full date, not just the year.</p>
    <p>Current age is calculated by finding the number of complete years that have elapsed since the birthday. If today's month and day are before the birthday month and day, one year is subtracted from the simple year difference. This gives the standard social age that people use in everyday conversation and on legal documents.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Current Age = Current Year - Birth Year - (1 if birthday hasn't passed yet this year)</code>
    </div>
    <p>The calculator also shows the age in months and days for additional precision. A person born on May 15, 1990 would be 35 years, 9 months, and 23 days old on March 8, 2026. This level of detail is useful for pediatric growth tracking, insurance quotes, and legal matters where exact age in months or days may be relevant.</p>
    <p>In some Asian cultures, a different age counting system is used. In the Korean age system (which was officially phased out in 2023 but is still culturally relevant), a person is 1 year old at birth and gains a year every January 1 rather than on their birthday. This can make someone one or two years older in Korean age compared to international age. The calculator on this page uses the international age system standard in the United States and most Western countries.</p>

    <h2>The "Half Your Age Plus 7" Rule</h2>
    <p>The "half your age plus 7" rule is a popular social guideline used to determine the minimum socially acceptable age of a romantic partner. To apply the rule, take the older person's age, divide it by 2, and add 7. The result is the minimum age of a partner that falls within the socially conventional range. The younger person's age should be at or above this number for the relationship to be considered within the norm by this guideline.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Minimum Partner Age = (Older Person's Age / 2) + 7</code>
    </div>
    <p>For example, if the older partner is 30, the minimum age under this rule would be 30 divided by 2 plus 7, which equals 22. A 40-year-old's minimum would be 27, and a 50-year-old's minimum would be 32. The rule produces increasingly wider acceptable ranges as people age: at 20, the range is 17 to 26; at 30, the range is 22 to 46; at 50, the range is 32 to 86.</p>
    <p>The origin of this rule is debated. It has been traced to a 1901 French novel where it was originally described as the ideal age for a bride (half the groom's age plus 7), not as a minimum. Over the decades, it evolved into a minimum age guideline and became widespread through pop culture, advice columns, and internet discussions. The rule gained significant visibility when it appeared in an XKCD webcomic and in the television show Parks and Recreation.</p>
    <p>It is important to emphasize that this rule is a cultural curiosity and conversational tool, not a scientific or psychological standard. Healthy relationships depend on factors far more important than age, including emotional maturity, shared values, communication skills, and mutual respect. Many couples with age gaps outside this rule have fulfilling, long-lasting relationships. The rule also has limitations at younger ages (it suggests a 14-year-old could date a 14-year-old, which is reasonable, but at very young ages the formula breaks down) and does not account for individual circumstances, cultural norms, or the diversity of human relationships.</p>

    <h2>Age Gap Statistics in Relationships</h2>
    <p>Research on age gaps in romantic relationships reveals some interesting patterns across different cultures and time periods. Understanding these statistics can provide context for your own age difference calculation, though it is worth remembering that statistics describe averages and norms, not right or wrong.</p>
    <p>In the United States, the average age difference between married heterosexual couples is approximately 2.3 years, with the husband being older in the majority of cases. According to census data, about 64 percent of married couples have an age gap of 0 to 3 years. Approximately 20 percent have a gap of 4 to 6 years, 10 percent have a gap of 7 to 10 years, and about 6 percent have a gap of more than 10 years. The husband is older in roughly 64 percent of couples, the wife is older in about 23 percent, and partners are the same age in about 13 percent.</p>
    <p>Age gaps tend to be larger in second and subsequent marriages compared to first marriages. This is partly because the pool of available partners widens with age and partly because people in later marriages often prioritize compatibility over age proximity. Celebrity relationships with large age gaps receive disproportionate media attention but are not representative of the general population.</p>
    <p>Cultural norms around age gaps vary significantly worldwide. In many Western countries, large age gaps (especially with an older man and younger woman) have become less common over the past century as women's economic independence has increased. In some cultures, particularly in parts of South Asia, the Middle East, and West Africa, larger age gaps remain common and culturally accepted, often with the husband being significantly older.</p>
    <p>Research on relationship satisfaction and age gaps shows mixed results. Some studies find that couples with very large age gaps (10 or more years) report slightly lower relationship satisfaction on average, particularly as they age and enter different life stages simultaneously. However, other research finds no significant correlation between age gap and relationship quality when other factors like income, education, and communication skills are controlled for. The quality of a relationship depends far more on the individuals involved than on the numerical gap between their birthdays.</p>

    <h2>Legal Considerations for Age Differences</h2>
    <p>While the social aspects of age differences are a matter of personal preference and cultural norms, there are legal considerations that apply in specific contexts. These vary by jurisdiction and are important to understand.</p>
    <p>The age of majority, when a person is legally considered an adult, is 18 in most US states and many countries worldwide. Before this age, individuals have limited legal capacity to enter contracts, consent to medical treatment, and make certain life decisions. Some states set the age of majority at 19 or 21 for specific purposes such as purchasing alcohol.</p>
    <p>Age of consent laws, which define the legal age for consenting to certain activities, vary by state and country. In the United States, the age of consent ranges from 16 to 18 depending on the state, and many states have close-in-age exemptions (often called Romeo and Juliet laws) that reduce or eliminate penalties when both individuals are close in age. These laws are complex and vary significantly, so anyone with questions about specific legal situations should consult a local attorney.</p>
    <p>In employment law, the Age Discrimination in Employment Act protects workers aged 40 and older from discrimination based on age. In insurance, age differences between spouses can affect premiums and coverage options. In family law, the age of each parent and the age gap between partners may be considered in custody decisions, though this varies by jurisdiction and is just one of many factors courts examine.</p>
    <p>For immigration purposes, the age of a petitioner and beneficiary can affect visa eligibility and processing. The US Department of State uses the Child Status Protection Act to determine whether a child has aged out of certain immigration benefits, where the exact age in years and days matters significantly.</p>

    <h2>How to Calculate Days Between Two Dates</h2>
    <p>The total number of days between two dates is useful for many calculations beyond age difference. It appears in financial calculations (day counts for bond pricing), legal deadlines, project management timelines, and medical contexts (gestational age, treatment schedules). The calculator above automatically computes this value, but understanding the method is helpful.</p>
    <p>The most reliable method converts both dates to a continuous day count, often using the Julian Day Number system or a similar epoch-based approach. In JavaScript, the Date object represents dates as milliseconds since January 1, 1970 (the Unix epoch). Subtracting two Date objects gives the difference in milliseconds, which can be divided by 86,400,000 (the number of milliseconds in a day) to get the difference in days.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Total Days = |Date2 - Date1| / (1000 &times; 60 &times; 60 &times; 24)</code>
    </div>
    <p>This method automatically accounts for leap years, varying month lengths, and calendar irregularities. A leap year occurs every 4 years, except for years divisible by 100, except for years divisible by 400 (which are leap years). So 2000 was a leap year, but 1900 was not. The average year is 365.2425 days long, but individual years are either 365 or 366 days.</p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How do you calculate the age difference between two people?</summary>
        <p>Subtract the earlier birthday from the later birthday to get the age difference in years, months, and days. Start with the days: if the later date's day is smaller, borrow from the months. Then compare months: if the later date's month is smaller after borrowing, borrow from the years by adding 12 months. Finally subtract the years. For the total days apart, convert both dates to a day count and subtract. For example, if Person A was born January 15, 1990 and Person B on March 20, 1995, the difference is 5 years, 2 months, and 5 days. The calculator handles all the complexities of varying month lengths and leap years automatically, giving you precise results in seconds.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the "half your age plus 7" rule?</summary>
        <p>The half your age plus 7 rule is a social guideline suggesting the minimum acceptable age of a romantic partner. Take the older person's age, divide by 2, and add 7. For a 30-year-old, the minimum partner age would be 30 divided by 2 plus 7, which equals 22. The rule originated from a 1901 French book and has since become a widely referenced pop culture guideline. It produces a wider acceptable range as people age. At 20, the acceptable range is 17 to 26. At 40, it is 27 to 66. This is purely a cultural convention and not a scientific measure of relationship compatibility. Healthy relationships depend on emotional maturity, shared values, and mutual respect, not adherence to a mathematical formula.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the average age difference between couples?</summary>
        <p>In the United States, the average age difference between married couples is about 2.3 years, with the husband being older in the majority of cases. Approximately 64 percent of married couples have an age gap of 0 to 3 years, 20 percent have a gap of 4 to 6 years, 10 percent have a gap of 7 to 10 years, and about 6 percent have a gap of more than 10 years. These statistics vary significantly by culture and region. Age gaps tend to be larger in second marriages compared to first marriages. Research on relationship satisfaction shows mixed results regarding age gaps, with most studies concluding that communication, shared values, and compatibility matter far more than the numerical difference in ages.</p>
      </details>
    </div>

